As React applications grow, component communication often becomes more difficult than expected. If you’ve worked with React long enough, you’ve probably run into the same recurring problem: two components that have nothing to do with each other in the tree need to talk.
A button buried deep inside the component tree needs to show a toast notification. Maybe a Toast component needs to fire when any part of the app calls notify(). A successful API request should refresh a widget somewhere else on the page. A login event needs to notify several independent features. Maybe a Sidebar filter needs to update a Chart three levels away without threading props through six layers, or wrapping half your app in a Context Provider just to solve one narrow problem.
The default solution is often one of these:

• Lift state higher in the component tree.

• Pass callbacks through multiple layers of components.

• Introduce global state management.
While these approaches work, they can sometimes solve the wrong problem.
The real requirement is often not shared state but event communication.
This is where the Publish–Subscribe (Pub/Sub) pattern shines.
What Pub/Sub Actually Is
The pattern has three players:

• Publishers emit events without knowing who (if anyone) is listening.

• Subscribers listen for events without knowing who published them.

• A broker (sometimes called an event bus) sits in the middle, routing messages from publishers to subscribers.
Publisher → Event Bus → SubscribersA component simply announces that something happened.
Another component decides whether it cares.
Why Not Just Use Context or Redux?
Before writing any code, it’s worth being honest about when pub/sub is the right tool, because it isn’t always.
React Context is great for values that many components need to read — theme, locale, authenticated user. It’s less great for high-frequency events, because updating context re-renders every consumer, and it forces you to define the shape of your state upfront.
Redux, Zustand, etc. are built for shared state — data that needs to persist and be read from many places. They come with devtools, middleware, and predictable update flows, but that’s often more ceremony than you need for a one-off “hey, something happened” signal.
Pub/sub shines for events, not state. Things like:

• “A toast notification should appear”

• “The user pressed Ctrl+K to open command palette”

• “A WebSocket message arrived”

• “Analytics: track this interaction”
These are fire-and-forget signals, not data you need to keep around and re-render on. That’s the sweet spot for pub/sub in a React app.
Building a Minimal Event Bus on Top of the DOM
Many Pub/Sub tutorials build a custom event emitter using arrays and maps. But browsers already ship with an event system capable of doing exactly this. document itself can act as the event broker:
const EventBus = (function () {
function subscribe(event, callback) {
document.addEventListener(event, callback);
return function () {
document.removeEventListener(event, callback);
};
} function publish(event, data) {
const nativeEvent = new CustomEvent(event, { detail: data });
document.dispatchEvent(nativeEvent);
}
return { subscribe, publish };
})();
Wiring It Into React with a Hook
The trick to using this cleanly in React is wrapping the subscription in a useEffect, so subscriptions are set up on mount and torn down on unmount:
// useSubscribe.js
import { useEffect } from 'react';
import { EventBus } from './eventBus';export function useSubscribe(event, callback) {
useEffect(() => {
const unsubscribe = EventBus.subscribe(event, callback);
return unsubscribe;
}, [event, callback]);
}
Now any component can publish:
function SaveButton() {
const handleSave = () => {
// ...save logic
EventBus.publish('notification', { type: 'success', message: 'Saved!' });
}; return <button onClick={handleSave}>Save</button>;
}
And any other component, anywhere in the tree, can subscribe. Remember that the callback receives a native Event, so the payload lives at event.detail:
javascript
function ToastContainer() {
const [toasts, setToasts] = useState([]); useSubscribe('notification', (event) => {
setToasts((prev) => [...prev, event.detail]);
});
return (
<div className="toast-container">
{toasts.map((toast, i) => (
<div key={i} className={`toast toast-${toast.type}`}>
{toast.message}
</div>
))}
</div>
);
}
SaveButton and ToastContainer never import each other. They could live in completely different feature folders, written by different teams, and neither would need to change if the other moved.
Potential Drawbacks
Pub/Sub is powerful, but it should be used selectively.
Event Names Become Global
Since events are attached to document, naming collisions are possible.
This is not ideal:
open
close
update
saveNamespaced events are much safer:
auth:login
cart:item-added
toast:show
modal:openDebugging Can Become Harder
Because communication is indirect, tracing event flows may require additional logging.
Unlike props, event dependencies are not immediately visible in the component tree.
Final Thoughts
The Publish–Subscribe pattern is not a replacement for React state management.
It solves a different problem.
When components need to react to something that happened rather than share data that exists, Pub/Sub can dramatically simplify the architecture.
The most interesting part is that you may not need another library at all.
The browser already includes an event system that has been battle-tested for decades.
Sometimes the simplest event bus is the one that’s been sitting inside document all along.
